04059nam a22005535i 9780822393788DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223937887 a10.1515/97808223937882doi  a(DE-B1597)551762  a(OCoLC)714085017  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1995.9.L48 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4365266431 aCorber, Robert J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCold War Femme :bLesbianism, National Identity, and Hollywood Cinema /cRobert J. Corber. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (236 p.) :b14 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Reclaiming the " Lost Sex" -- tChapter One. Representing the Femme -- tChapter Two. Lesbian Unintelligibility -- tChapter Three. Recuperating Femme Femininity -- tChapter Four. Joan Crawford's Padded Shoulders -- tChapter Five. Remaking Bette Davis -- tChapter Six. Doris Day's Queer Normativity -- tConclusion. Killing Off the Femme -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his bestselling book The Grapevine: A Report on the Secret World of the Lesbian (1965), Jess Stearn announced that, contrary to the assumptions of many Americans, most lesbians appeared indistinguishable from other women. They could mingle "congenially in conventional society." Some were popular sex symbols; some were married to unsuspecting husbands. Robert J. Corber contends that The Grapevine exemplified a homophobic Cold War discourse that portrayed the femme as an invisible threat to the nation. Underlying this panic was the widespread fear that college-educated women would reject marriage and motherhood as aspirations, weakening the American family and compromising the nation's ability to defeat totalitarianism. Corber argues that Cold War homophobia transformed ideas about lesbianism in the United States. In the early twentieth century, homophobic discourse had focused on gender identity: the lesbian was a masculine woman. During the Cold War, the lesbian was reconceived as a woman attracted to other women. Corber develops his argument by analyzing representations of lesbianism in Hollywood movies of the 1950s and 1960s, and in the careers of some of the era's biggest female stars. He examines treatments of the femme in All About Eve, The Children's Hour, and Marnie, and he explores the impact of Cold War homophobia on the careers of Joan Crawford, Bette Davis, and Doris Day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aCold WarxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aLesbianism in motion pictures. 0aWomen in popular culturezUnited States. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393788zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393788423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822393788.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles